// NCMHCE — Part 3 (Q121-210)
var _qs = window.QUESTIONS_DATA["ncmhce"] || (window.QUESTIONS_DATA["ncmhce"] = []);

_qs.push(
{id:"ncm-121",q:"A 16-year-old has been binge drinking. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Send to AA","Conduct a comprehensive assessment (use severity, mental health, family functioning, safety, peer influence) and engage the teen and family","Hospitalize","Recommend a 28-day program"],answer:0,explanation:"Adolescent substance use: comprehensive assessment first. Use severity (CRAFFT, frequency, amount, consequences), mental health (depression, anxiety, trauma, ADHD), family functioning, peer influence, school, safety (driving, sexual risk). Use MI to engage. Involve the family. Treatment may include family therapy (MDFT, FFT), MI/CBT, possibly residential if severe. Don't just refer to AA. Don't hospitalize (rarely). Don't push residential without assessment."},
{id:"ncm-122",q:"A 50-year-old client with chronic insomnia is taking benzodiazepines. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop immediately","Discuss a slow taper, recommend CBT-I, and coordinate with the prescriber","Increase the dose","Switch to alcohol"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term benzodiazepines for insomnia: not recommended (dependence, falls, cognitive effects, rebound insomnia on stopping). The counselor discusses a slow taper (withdrawal can be life-threatening — seizures). Coordinate with the prescriber. Recommend CBT-I (first-line, durable). Don't stop abruptly. Don't increase. Don't replace with alcohol (much worse). Address: reasons for use, alternatives, sleep hygiene, anxiety or pain."},
{id:"ncm-123",q:"A 40-year-old client has been through a traumatic divorce. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to move on","Assess for PTSD, depression, complex grief, and provide trauma-focused therapy as needed","Hospitalize","Refer to a lawyer"],answer:1,explanation:"Traumatic divorce (especially with abuse, infidelity, custody battles): assess for PTSD, complex grief, depression, anxiety. Provide trauma-focused therapy as needed. Many people experience divorce as a traumatic event. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize (rarely). Don't refer to a lawyer (out of scope). Validate the experience. Address the impact, meaning, and adjustment. Sometimes includes co-parenting counseling."},
{id:"ncm-124",q:"A 17-year-old has been cutting for 2 years. The parents are aware but the cutting continues. The counselor should:",options:["Hospitalize for each episode","Use DBT, address family accommodation, and engage the family in treatment","Tell the teen to stop","Ignore it"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic self-harm: DBT is evidence-based. Address: family accommodation (the family accommodates to reduce distress, which often enables), engage the family in treatment (DBT family sessions or parent coaching), validate, build alternative skills, and address underlying issues. Hospitalize only if imminent risk. Don't tell them to stop. Don't ignore. Don't promise a cure. Long-term work. Treat comorbidities (depression, anxiety, trauma, BPD)."},
{id:"ncm-125",q:"A 60-year-old client has been recently widowed. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend moving","Provide grief support, normalize the experience, monitor for complicated grief or depression, and engage the client's support system","Hospitalize","Recommend new medication"],answer:1,explanation:"Recent bereavement: grief is normal. Provide support, normalize the experience, monitor for complicated grief / prolonged grief disorder or Major Depressive Disorder, engage the support system. Many people grieve without intervention. Don't recommend moving (premature). Don't hospitalize (rarely). Don't recommend medication for normal grief. Some clients benefit from grief support groups or grief therapy. Cultural sensitivity. Don't push. Don't make the grief medical."},
{id:"ncm-126",q:"A 25-year-old client has been struggling with the realization they are gay. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to keep it private","Affirm the client's identity, address minority stress, explore family/cultural/religious factors, and provide affirming resources","Recommend conversion therapy","Refer to a religious counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"Sexual identity exploration: affirmative approach. Many LGBTQ+ individuals experience distress during this exploration, often from family, religion, or culture. Address minority stress (distal and proximal stressors, internalized homophobia). Explore family/cultural/religious factors. Provide resources (PFLAG, Trevor Project, HRC, GLAAD). Don't tell them to keep it private. Don't recommend conversion therapy (unethical, harmful). Refer to a religious counselor only if affirming; otherwise unhelpful or harmful."},
{id:"ncm-127",q:"A 35-year-old client is in recovery from opioid use disorder. They are starting a new job. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to avoid stress","Develop a relapse prevention plan, identify triggers, use coping skills, build the support system, and address the new stressors","Recommend they not work","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"New job in recovery: support the client's recovery. Develop a relapse prevention plan: identify triggers (people, places, things, emotions), use coping skills (without substances), engage support system (sponsor, AA/NA, friends), and address new stressors. Don't avoid stress (unrealistic). Don't keep them from working (healthy recovery). Don't hospitalize. Celebrate the milestone. Address the new challenges (money, time, identity, coworkers). Build healthy routines."},
{id:"ncm-128",q:"A 14-year-old has been refusing to leave the house due to severe social anxiety. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Recommend homeschooling","Conduct a comprehensive assessment and develop a graded return-to-school and social plan using CBT and exposure","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to force attendance"],answer:1,explanation:"Comprehensive assessment: social anxiety severity, comorbidities (depression, other anxiety, OCD, autism), school environment, family dynamics. Develop a graduated exposure plan: home, then small outings, then school. CBT (cognitive restructuring, social skills, exposure) + SSRIs. Engage the family and school. Don't force attendance. Don't recommend homeschooling (worsens anxiety). Don't hospitalize (rarely). Address the avoidance pattern early; it worsens with time."},
{id:"ncm-129",q:"A 28-year-old client has been in therapy for 3 months and has not improved. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Terminate treatment","Reassess: diagnosis, treatment fidelity, adherence, comorbidities, the therapeutic alliance, and outside stressors","Switch to a different counselor","Tell the client to work harder"],answer:1,explanation:"Reassess. Common reasons for non-response: incorrect diagnosis, comorbidities (substance, personality, medical), treatment not delivered correctly (fidelity), adherence (medication, homework, session frequency), poor therapeutic alliance, or external stressors. Don't terminate. Don't refer away. Don't blame the client. Consult supervision. Reassess and adjust the plan. Sometimes a different approach or modality is needed."},
{id:"ncm-130",q:"A 40-year-old client has been binge eating and inducing vomiting for 6 months. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Hospitalize","Conduct a comprehensive assessment: eating behaviors, medical status, psychiatric comorbidities, and provide CBT-E","Refer to a nutritionist","Tell them to stop"],answer:1,explanation:"Bulimia: comprehensive assessment first. Medical status (electrolytes, dental, GI), eating behaviors (frequency, triggers), psychiatric comorbidities (depression, anxiety, OCD, substance), body image, family, functioning. CBT-E (Fairburn) is first-line: regular eating, weekly weighing, cognitive restructuring, addressing overvaluation of weight/shape. SSRIs (fluoxetine). Don't hospitalize (outpatient usually sufficient). Don't refer to a nutritionist only. Don't tell them to stop. Address the binge-purge cycle directly."},
{id:"ncm-131",q:"A 7-year-old has been wetting the bed. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Punish the child","Assess for medical causes, family stressors, trauma, and use behavioral interventions","Refer to a psychiatrist","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Enuresis: assess for medical causes (UTI, constipation, diabetes, sleep apnea), family stressors, trauma, abuse, recent changes. Behavioral interventions: bedwetting alarms (most effective), fluid restriction at night, scheduled voiding, positive reinforcement, education. Address shame. Don't punish. Don't hospitalize (not appropriate). Don't refer to a psychiatrist unless comorbid. Engage the family. The child is not doing it on purpose. Common, often self-resolves."},
{id:"ncm-132",q:"A 50-year-old client has been having flashbacks from a childhood trauma. The counselor should:",options:["Use prolonged exposure immediately","Begin with stabilization and trauma-informed care, then use trauma-focused therapy (PE, EMDR, CPT)","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Ignore it"],answer:1,explanation:"Adult trauma work: three phases (Herman, Courtois). (1) Stabilization (safety, regulation, skills, support), (2) Processing (trauma memory work, EMDR, PE, CPT), (3) Integration. Don't jump to PE if the client is not stable. Phase 1 is essential. Address: safety, current triggers, coping skills, emotion regulation, support, and the therapeutic relationship. Then process the trauma memories. Pace matters. Don't do this alone - consult. Trauma-informed care is essential."},
{id:"ncm-133",q:"A 19-year-old has been diagnosed with bipolar I disorder and is on lithium. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stay positive","Provide psychoeducation, monitor for side effects and warning signs, support medication adherence, and develop a relapse prevention plan","Hospitalize","Tell them they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Bipolar I with lithium: psychoeducation (lithium requires monitoring — thyroid, kidney, narrow therapeutic window), medication adherence, warning signs (sleep, mood, energy, activity), relapse prevention plan (regular routines, sleep hygiene, stress management, support, professional contact), and ongoing therapy (CBT, IPSRT — Interpersonal and Social Rhythm Therapy, family-focused therapy). Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't declare cured (chronic condition). Address stigma, identity, and support. Many clients do well with lithium + therapy."},
{id:"ncm-134",q:"A 30-year-old client with obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) is also depressed. The counselor should:",options:["Treat only the OCD first","Treat both concurrently: ERP for OCD, CBT/BA for depression, and possibly medication (an SSRI can address both)","Refer to a psychiatrist and end the session","Tell the client to focus on one issue at a time"],answer:1,explanation:"Comorbid OCD and depression: common. Treat both concurrently. An SSRI (often at higher doses for OCD) can address both. CBT/BA for depression. ERP for OCD. Family involvement if accommodation is an issue. Don't focus on one issue (often both need attention). Don't refer away. Treat the whole person. Many people with OCD also have depression, anxiety, or other comorbidities."},
{id:"ncm-135",q:"A 50-year-old client with chronic mental illness has been in supported housing for 5 years. They report being lonely. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to be grateful","Address the social isolation, support engagement in community activities, peer support, and meaningful roles","Recommend a different housing","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Loneliness in chronic mental illness: address it. Social isolation is a major issue. Support: peer support, community activities, day programs, volunteer work, supported employment (IPS), groups, classes, religious community (if appropriate). Don't dismiss. Don't recommend different housing (just moves the problem). Don't hospitalize. Many people in supported housing are isolated. Recovery-oriented care addresses the whole person. Build the social network."},
{id:"ncm-136",q:"A 22-year-old client with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) has just started a new job. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to figure it out","Provide support, address workplace accommodations, use visual supports and clear structure, and collaborate with the employer","Hospitalize","Recommend quitting"],answer:1,explanation:"ASD and employment: support the client. Address workplace accommodations (clear expectations, written instructions, predictable routine, sensory accommodations, mentor, training). Use strengths-based approach. Many adults with ASD have unique strengths (detail, focus, memory, honesty). Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend quitting. Collaborate with the employer. Many people with ASD are successful with proper support. Address the social demands and the unique strengths."},
{id:"ncm-137",q:"A 14-year-old has been bullying a younger student. The counselor should:",options:["Suspend the student","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, address the behavior, engage the family, and provide restorative interventions","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to be stricter"],answer:1,explanation:"Bullying: comprehensive assessment. Why is the child bullying? (Modeling, peer dynamics, social skills deficits, trauma, conduct disorder, ADHD, emotional dysregulation). Address the behavior, engage the family, use restorative interventions (apology, restitution, dialogue with the victim if appropriate), teach empathy and alternatives. Don't suspend (often unhelpful). Don't hospitalize (not appropriate). Don't rely on stricter parenting. The victim also needs support."},
{id:"ncm-138",q:"A 45-year-old client with chronic depression has been struggling with rumination. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to think positive","Use CBT techniques (cognitive restructuring, behavioral experiments), behavioral activation, and address the rumination pattern directly","Switch to psychoanalysis","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Rumination in depression: a maintaining factor. CBT (cognitive restructuring, behavioral experiments, behavioral activation, mindfulness-based cognitive therapy — MBCT) directly targets rumination. Address: triggers, function, and consequences of rumination. Schedule activity. Don't tell them to 'think positive' (dismissive). Don't switch to psychoanalysis (less effective for rumination). Don't hospitalize (not appropriate for rumination alone). Train attention shift. MBCT specifically addresses depressive rumination."},
{id:"ncm-139",q:"A 35-year-old client has been sober for 1 year. They are concerned about relapse after an argument with their spouse. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them relapse is part of recovery","Validate the concern, develop a plan to address the conflict without substance use, identify triggers, and use coping skills","Recommend inpatient","Tell them to leave the relationship"],answer:1,explanation:"Sobriety stress: validate the concern, help the client develop a plan to handle the conflict (without substances), identify triggers, and use coping skills. Don't tell them relapse is part of recovery (it's common but not inevitable). Don't recommend inpatient (not appropriate for this stress). Don't tell them to leave the relationship. Couples therapy may be appropriate (when the partner engages). Address: communication, problem-solving, recovery support, and emotion regulation. Many couples argue; using substances isn't the answer."},
{id:"ncm-140",q:"A 12-year-old has been refusing to attend school due to anxiety about a particular teacher. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend a different teacher","Conduct an assessment, address the school situation (with the school's collaboration), use CBT and exposure, and engage the family","Tell the parents to force attendance","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"School refusal for a specific reason (the teacher): assess. Address the school situation (with collaboration, not unilateral changes). CBT and graded exposure (the child returns to school with coping skills). Family engagement. Don't recommend a different teacher (avoidance reinforces anxiety). Don't force attendance. Don't hospitalize. Many school refusal cases resolve with proper intervention. Address the specific anxiety, the child's coping, and the school environment."},
{id:"ncm-141",q:"A 25-year-old client has been experiencing hallucinations and delusions for the first time. The counselor should:",options:["Begin supportive counseling","Refer for urgent psychiatric evaluation, engage the family, and consider a comprehensive treatment program (CST, NAVIGATE)","Tell the client it's just stress","Hospitalize immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"First-episode psychosis: urgent psychiatric evaluation. Coordinate with the family. Consider Coordinated Specialty Care (CST / NAVIGATE) — evidence-based for first-episode psychosis. Components: low-dose antipsychotic, family education, supported employment/education, case management, CBT for psychosis (CBTp). Early intervention improves outcomes. Don't dismiss as stress. Don't hospitalize immediately (depends on safety). Don't just do supportive counseling alone. The duration of untreated psychosis correlates with worse outcomes. Engage the family."},
{id:"ncm-142",q:"A 35-year-old client is in therapy for severe childhood trauma. They report feeling 'unsafe' in their body. The counselor should:",options:["Begin exposure to trauma memories","Use stabilization, grounding, body-based approaches (somatic experiencing, sensorimotor psychotherapy, DBT), and respect the client's pace","Tell them to relax","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Severe trauma: body holds the trauma. Use stabilization, grounding, body-based approaches (Somatic Experiencing, sensorimotor psychotherapy, EMDR resourcing, DBT skills), and respect the client's pace. The 'window of tolerance' concept: stay within it. Don't jump to exposure to trauma memories (risk of re-traumatization). Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize unless imminent risk. Process the trauma only after the client has resources. Engage the body carefully. Trust the client's pacing."},
{id:"ncm-143",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for anxiety for 6 months. The counselor notices the client is now in a depressive episode. The counselor should:",options:["Continue with the same treatment","Reassess, address the depression, consider medication referral, and adjust the treatment plan","Hospitalize","Discharge"],answer:1,explanation:"New depression during anxiety treatment: reassess. Address the new presentation. Consider medication referral (if not already), CBT for depression, behavioral activation, assessment for bipolar (if appropriate), and adjustment of the treatment plan. Don't continue unchanged. Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Don't discharge. Many clients with anxiety also develop depression. Sometimes anxiety is a symptom of depression or vice versa. Treat the whole person."},
{id:"ncm-144",q:"A 40-year-old client with a new diagnosis of multiple sclerosis is having difficulty coping. The counselor should:",options:["Refer to a neurologist only","Provide support, use CBT, address grief, engage the family, and collaborate with the medical team","Tell them to stay positive","Recommend ECT"],answer:1,explanation:"Adjustment to a new, serious medical diagnosis: support, CBT, address grief (loss of function, identity, future, abilities), engage the family, collaborate with the medical team (neurologist, nurse, OT, PT). Don't refer only to the neurologist (psychosocial care is important). Don't tell them to stay positive (dismissive). Don't recommend ECT (not appropriate). Address the impact, the uncertainty, the family, the work, the meaning. Many people with MS benefit from counseling and support groups."},
{id:"ncm-145",q:"A 50-year-old client has been sober for 5 years. They are considering drinking 'just one' to celebrate a milestone. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they can never drink again","Explore the client's thoughts, develop a plan, address triggers, and remind of the decision","Encourage the slip","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Long-term sobriety: explore the client's thinking. Don't tell them they can never drink (some clients in moderation-based recovery succeed; the counselor supports informed choice). Don't encourage the slip. Don't hospitalize. Develop a plan: identify the situation, identify triggers, use coping skills, engage the sponsor, attend a meeting, talk to the counselor, and remind themselves of their reasons. Many people celebrate milestones with alcohol; recovery is a long game. The counselor supports the client's chosen path."},
{id:"ncm-146",q:"A 6-year-old has been exhibiting severe anxiety. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Begin CBT","Conduct a multi-informant assessment (parent, teacher, child) and engage the family in treatment","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to ignore the behavior"],answer:1,explanation:"Child anxiety: comprehensive multi-informant assessment. Engage the family (parent training for anxious children is a key component). CBT adapted for children, parent training (e.g., Cool Kids program), family therapy, school collaboration. Don't hospitalize. Don't tell parents to ignore. Don't start therapy before assessment. Common in children; many effective treatments. Address the family accommodation and modeling. Don't tell the child to 'be brave' without skills."},
{id:"ncm-147",q:"A 20-year-old client with OCD has been engaging in mental compulsions (e.g., counting, praying). The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Develop a hierarchy that includes mental compulsions, teach exposure to thoughts while preventing the mental response, and address beliefs about responsibility","Ignore the mental compulsions","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Mental compulsions in OCD: target them in ERP. Build a hierarchy that includes mental acts (counting, praying, mental reviewing). Exposure to thoughts (e.g., recording and listening) while preventing the mental response. Address beliefs about responsibility, over-importance of thoughts, and need to control them. Don't dismiss. Don't ignore. Don't hospitalize. Many clients with OCD have only mental compulsions, which are easy to miss. ERP can be effective."},
{id:"ncm-148",q:"A 70-year-old client has been admitted to a nursing home. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend a different home","Address the adjustment, grief, and losses; engage the family; use reminiscence therapy and CBT as appropriate; and address depression or anxiety","Hospitalize","Tell them to make the best of it"],answer:1,explanation:"Adjustment to nursing home: address the adjustment, grief (loss of home, independence, abilities, future), and losses. Engage the family. Use reminiscence therapy (reviewing life, finding meaning, sharing), CBT for depression/anxiety as appropriate. Many residents have depression. Don't recommend a different home. Don't hospitalize. Don't tell them to 'make the best of it' (dismissive). Address: control, identity, family, meaning, relationships, and engagement. Quality of life matters."},
{id:"ncm-149",q:"A 28-year-old client with severe insomnia has been drinking alcohol to fall asleep. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to keep drinking","Address the self-medication, rule out alcohol use disorder, treat the insomnia (CBT-I), and address the function of alcohol","Hospitalize for alcohol withdrawal","Refer to AA immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Alcohol and insomnia: common cycle. Address the self-medication, assess for AUD, treat the insomnia (CBT-I is first-line, not alcohol), address the function of alcohol (often relaxation and sleep). Don't dismiss. Don't tell them to keep drinking (worsens). Don't hospitalize (unless significant withdrawal risk). Don't just refer to AA (may not be the issue). Address: sleep hygiene, alcohol use, anxiety, and coping. Many people with insomnia use alcohol; it disrupts sleep architecture over time."},
{id:"ncm-150",q:"A 32-year-old client has been hearing voices telling them to hurt others. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Have a long discussion about the voices","Immediately assess for safety (specificity of threat, target, plan, means, intent), consider hospitalization, and contact the intended target if necessary (duty to warn)","Ignore the command hallucinations","Tell them the voices are not real"],answer:1,explanation:"Command hallucinations to hurt others: IMMEDIATE safety assessment. Specificity, target, plan, means, intent. Hospitalize if necessary. Duty to warn/protect (Tarasoff) — contact the intended target, law enforcement, and take reasonable protective action. Don't have a long discussion (safety first). Don't ignore. Don't dismiss. Don't just tell them the voices are not real (not helpful). Document. May need emergency medication. Engage the treatment team. Safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-151",q:"A 16-year-old has been in a residential treatment program. The parents are demanding the teen stay longer. The counselor should:",options:["Keep the teen in residential","Base the length of stay on clinical need, work with the family, and develop a transition plan","Discharge immediately","Send to a different program"],answer:1,explanation:"Residential length of stay: based on clinical need, not family pressure. Use clear, individualized treatment goals. Discuss with the family, the team, and the teen. Develop a transition plan. Don't keep them longer than needed (worsens outcomes). Don't discharge abruptly. Don't bounce between programs. Use the family work to address the parents' concerns (e.g., guilt, fear, lack of trust). Effective residential is a step, not a destination."},
{id:"ncm-152",q:"A 14-year-old has been suicidal and is now stabilized. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge from treatment","Develop an ongoing safety plan, address underlying issues, engage the family, and continue regular therapy","Hospitalize for months","Tell the teen they're fine"],answer:1,explanation:"After stabilization: ongoing care. Safety plan, family engagement, individual therapy (DBT, CBT, family therapy), address underlying issues, school support, and peer support. Don't discharge (transition is high-risk). Don't hospitalize for months (acute stabilization is brief). Don't tell the teen they're fine. Build the relationship, address the meaning, monitor for warning signs, and continue treatment. The work continues. Many teens do well with proper support."},
{id:"ncm-153",q:"A 45-year-old client with chronic depression has been on multiple antidepressants. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge as treatment-resistant","Continue to provide therapy, coordinate with the prescriber, address comorbidities, and consider alternative treatments (TMS, esketamine, MAOIs, augmentation)","Switch to a different counselor","Recommend ECT immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Treatment-resistant depression: continue to provide therapy (CBT, behavioral activation, IPT, MBCT), coordinate with the prescriber, address comorbidities (substance, anxiety, personality, medical, sleep), and consider alternative treatments (TMS, esketamine, MAOIs, lithium augmentation, atypical antipsychotic augmentation). Don't discharge. Don't refer away. Don't immediately recommend ECT (usually after multiple medication trials). Stay involved. Re-evaluate the diagnosis. Many 'treatment-resistant' cases respond with persistence."},
{id:"ncm-154",q:"A 30-year-old client has been binge drinking on weekends. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to quit immediately","Use MI, assess drinking pattern and consequences, and develop a plan based on the client's goals and motivation","Hospitalize","Recommend a 28-day program"],answer:1,explanation:"Binge drinking: MI, assess pattern, consequences, and the client's goals. Some clients may be appropriate for brief intervention, harm reduction, moderation, or abstinence. Match the treatment to the client. Don't demand abstinence. Don't hospitalize (rarely). Don't recommend residential (often unnecessary for binge drinking without severe dependence). The Stages of Change model: meet the client where they are. Many people reduce or quit drinking with brief intervention."},
{id:"ncm-155",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in a high-conflict relationship. The counselor should:",options:["Take sides","Explore the dynamics, the safety, and the cycle; use EFT or BCT; assess for abuse; and support informed decision-making","Tell them to leave","Recommend they stay together"],answer:1,explanation:"High-conflict relationships: explore the dynamics, the safety (abuse?), and the cycle. Use EFT or BCT frameworks. Assess for abuse (if present, safety first). Support the client's informed decision-making. Don't take sides. Don't tell them to leave (unless abuse). Don't tell them to stay (if it's unsafe). Address: communication, conflict resolution, attachment, and safety. Many couples can improve with therapy. Some shouldn't stay together. The counselor supports the client's choice."},
{id:"ncm-156",q:"A 25-year-old client has been experiencing auditory hallucinations for years but is not distressed by them. The counselor should:",options:["Hospitalize for psychosis","Conduct a comprehensive assessment; this may not be a disorder if there's no distress or impairment (consider cultural and religious context)","Recommend antipsychotic medication","Tell the client the voices are not real"],answer:1,explanation:"Auditory hallucinations without distress: may not be a disorder. Some cultures/religions have experiences considered normal. Some individuals have 'voice hearing' that doesn't require treatment. Comprehensive assessment: distress, impairment, content, function, and context. If not pathological, no treatment needed. Don't hospitalize (no distress/impairment). Don't medicate (if not pathological). Don't dismiss. Some voice hearers use peer support groups (e.g., the Hearing Voices Network)."},
{id:"ncm-157",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe depression. They have been stable for 6 months and want to terminate. The counselor should:",options:["Refuse","Discuss termination collaboratively, develop a relapse prevention plan, and offer follow-up options","Discharge immediately","Increase session frequency"],answer:1,explanation:"Collaborative termination: discuss, develop a relapse prevention plan (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), offer follow-up options (booster, as-needed), and end well. Don't refuse. Don't discharge abruptly. Don't increase frequency unnecessarily. The termination phase is therapeutic. Many clients do well in maintenance and want to test their skills. Some need a longer maintenance. The counselor supports informed choice and doesn't force continuation."},
{id:"ncm-158",q:"A 25-year-old client is in a violent relationship. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to leave immediately","Provide safety planning, resources, and support the client's autonomy; assess immediate danger; document","Tell them to stay for the children","Refer to couples therapy"],answer:1,explanation:"Intimate partner violence: safety planning, resources (hotline, shelter, legal advocacy), and support the client's autonomy. Assess immediate danger. Document (without judgment). Don't tell them to leave (often not safe immediately; the client knows the situation). Don't tell them to stay. Don't refer to couples therapy (unsafe; the abuser often blames the victim). Provide options. The client decides. Many people leave multiple times before leaving for good. Safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-159",q:"A 50-year-old client has been sober for 10 years. They are now dealing with a new mental health concern. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them recovery is more important","Address the new concern with appropriate treatment, in coordination with the recovery support system","Send back to AA","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"New mental health concern in long-term recovery: address it. The counselor provides appropriate treatment (CBT, BA, medication referral if needed) while honoring the recovery journey. Coordinate with the recovery support system. Don't dismiss the new concern. Don't just send back to AA. Don't hospitalize (rarely). Many people in long-term recovery have new mental health issues (anxiety, depression, trauma). Recovery is holistic. Treat the whole person. Engage the medical team as needed."},
{id:"ncm-160",q:"A 35-year-old client with OCD has been hospitalized due to severe contamination fears and rituals. The counselor in the hospital should:",options:["Reinforce the rituals to reduce anxiety","Conduct a brief assessment, begin or continue intensive ERP, and discharge to intensive outpatient or residential care","Tell the client they're fine","Recommend a medication change without coordination"],answer:1,explanation:"OCD inpatient: not the right setting for routine OCD treatment (often reinforces rituals). Best: brief assessment, support medication, begin or continue intensive ERP if the client is willing, and discharge to intensive outpatient, residential, or day treatment for ongoing ERP. The inpatient stay is brief. Don't reinforce the rituals. Don't dismiss. Don't change meds without coordination with the outpatient team. Plan for ongoing intensive treatment. ERP is the most effective, even when severe."},
{id:"ncm-161",q:"A 30-year-old client has been having recurrent thoughts of a past traumatic event. The counselor should:",options:["Begin EMDR immediately","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, build rapport and safety, and use a phased approach to trauma treatment","Tell the client to forget it","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Trauma work: phased approach. (1) Stabilization (safety, regulation, coping), (2) Processing (EMDR, PE, CPT), (3) Integration. Don't jump to EMDR. Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist (the counseling relationship is key). The work depends on safety, stability, and the alliance. Address the meaning, the impact, and the resources. Many people benefit. Build the foundation first."},
{id:"ncm-162",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of ADHD. The parents are skeptical of medication. The counselor should:",options:["Force medication","Provide accurate information, address the parents' concerns, discuss behavioral interventions (PMT), and respect the family's decision","Tell them they must medicate","Refer to a different counselor"],answer:1,explanation:"ADHD and parental skepticism: provide accurate information, address concerns, discuss the evidence for medication AND behavioral interventions (PMT, school supports, accommodations), and respect the family's decision. Don't force. Don't dismiss. Don't refer away. The therapeutic relationship is important. Many parents' concerns are valid (medication isn't the only option). Address the impact on the child's functioning. The counselor is an educator and advocate for the child."},
{id:"ncm-163",q:"A 45-year-old client with chronic pain has been using opioids for years. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Address comorbid depression/anxiety, use CBT for chronic pain, coordinate with the pain team, and discuss a slow taper if appropriate","Increase the dose","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic opioid use: address comorbid mental health, use CBT for chronic pain, coordinate with the pain team. Discuss a slow taper if appropriate (CDC guidelines, slower for long-term users), with monitoring for withdrawal, increased pain, and suicide risk. Don't force. Don't increase. Don't hospitalize. Many patients on long-term opioids have hyperalgesia. Engage the prescriber. The functional goal is improvement in function, not zero pain. Address the meaning, coping, and impact."},
{id:"ncm-164",q:"A 12-year-old has been suicidal. The school counselor has been involved. The clinical counselor should:",options:["Work in isolation","Collaborate with the school counselor, family, and medical team to ensure coordinated care","Tell the school to back off","Discharge the case to the school"],answer:1,explanation:"Suicidal child: collaborate. School counselor, family, medical team, and (if hospitalized) the inpatient team. Coordinated care is essential. Don't work in isolation. Don't dismiss the school counselor (they know the child in another context). Don't discharge to the school. The school is part of the safety net. Share information (with appropriate consent) about safety plan, warning signs, and how to respond. Many suicides are preventable with coordinated care."},
{id:"ncm-165",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in treatment for bulimia for 6 months. They have stopped binge-purging but still have body image concerns. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Continue to address body image, maintain the progress, develop a relapse prevention plan, and prepare for termination","Increase session frequency","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery from bulimia: continue to address body image (often the last symptom to improve). Maintain progress, develop a relapse prevention plan (triggers, coping skills, supports, what to do if it returns), and prepare for termination. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't increase frequency. Don't hospitalize. Many people with eating disorders need ongoing work on body image even after the binge-purge stops. The counselor supports the client through the last phases of recovery."},
{id:"ncm-166",q:"A 40-year-old client with chronic insomnia has been using over-the-counter sleep aids nightly. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to keep using","Address the OTC use (long-term safety concerns, tolerance), recommend CBT-I, and discuss tapering with the prescriber","Hospitalize","Refer to a sleep clinic only"],answer:1,explanation:"OTC sleep aids (antihistamines like diphenhydramine): long-term safety concerns (tolerance, anticholinergic effects, falls, cognitive effects in older adults). Recommend CBT-I (first-line, durable). Discuss tapering with the prescriber. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to a sleep clinic. Many people rely on OTC sleep aids. Address the underlying insomnia. Treat the whole person. Engage the medical team."},
{id:"ncm-167",q:"A 14-year-old has been in a gang. The counselor should:",options:["Report the gang","Engage the teen, assess safety, address reasons for gang involvement, use family therapy, and provide alternatives","Hospitalize","Tell the teen to stop immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Gang involvement: comprehensive assessment. Safety (the teen and others). Reasons for involvement (belonging, protection, identity, family, money, status). Use MI, family therapy (MDFT, FFT), and provide alternatives (mentorship, programs, school engagement). Don't report the gang (not effective, may damage trust). Don't hospitalize. Don't demand immediate cessation (often increases risk). Address: belonging, family, future, alternatives, and safety. Build the relationship."},
{id:"ncm-168",q:"A 30-year-old client has been experiencing symptoms of psychosis for 2 weeks. The counselor should:",options:["Wait and see","Refer for urgent psychiatric evaluation (this may be brief psychotic disorder, schizophreniform, or another psychotic condition)","Tell the client it's stress","Hospitalize immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Brief psychotic symptoms: urgent psychiatric evaluation. May be brief psychotic disorder (1 day-1 month, full return to premorbid), schizophreniform (1-6 months), schizophrenia (>6 months), substance-induced, or due to a medical condition. The duration determines the likely diagnosis. Don't wait. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize automatically (depends on safety). Early intervention helps. Coordinate with the family. Document."},
{id:"ncm-169",q:"A 50-year-old client with chronic mental illness has been hospitalized after a decompensation. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge as soon as medically stable","Begin discharge planning early, ensure continuity of care, coordinate with the outpatient team, and address the factors that led to the decompensation","Tell the client to be more compliant","Recommend institutional care"],answer:1,explanation:"Discharge planning: starts early. Continuity of care is critical (the transition is high-risk). Coordinate with the outpatient team, case management, ACT if appropriate, housing, family, and medical care. Address what led to the decompensation (medication non-adherence, substance use, stress, life changes). Don't discharge prematurely. Don't blame. Don't recommend long-term institutionalization. Many people with chronic mental illness can live in the community with proper support. Plan for the future."},
{id:"ncm-170",q:"A 25-year-old client with severe anorexia is being treated in the hospital. The counselor should:",options:["Refuse to see the client until weight is restored","Coordinate with the medical team, provide support, begin to address the underlying issues, and prepare for transition to ongoing treatment","Address only the eating disorder","Tell the family to force meals"],answer:1,explanation:"Anorexia inpatient: not the place to do deep therapy. Coordinate with the medical team. Provide support, build the relationship, address the underlying issues cautiously, and prepare for transition to FBT (adolescents) or CBT-E (adults). Don't refuse. Don't restrict. Don't tell the family to force. Refeeding is medical. The counselor's role: support, prepare, and plan for transition. The therapeutic work is in the transition, not in the hospital."},
{id:"ncm-171",q:"A 12-year-old has been stealing candy. The parents are asking for help. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Punish the child","Conduct a multi-informant assessment (parent, teacher, child), assess functioning, and provide age-appropriate interventions","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to be stricter"],answer:1,explanation:"Theft in children: assess first. Multi-informant (parent, teacher, child interview). Assessment: frequency, what they steal, family functioning, peers, school, mental health, trauma, abuse/neglect. Most child theft is not pathological (development, peer influence, opportunity). Interventions: clear expectations, consequences, restitution, and parent training. Don't punish excessively. Don't hospitalize. Don't just be stricter. Address the function. Most childhood theft is resolved with parental involvement and clear limits."},
{id:"ncm-172",q:"A 30-year-old client has been sober for 1 year. They are in a high-stress job. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to quit the job","Develop a stress management plan, address triggers, maintain recovery support, and use coping skills","Recommend inpatient","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery in a high-stress job: support. Develop a stress management plan (without substances), address triggers, maintain recovery support (sponsor, meetings, friends), use coping skills, ensure self-care, monitor for warning signs. Don't tell them to quit (work is a protective factor; may not be financially feasible). Don't recommend inpatient. Don't hospitalize. Many people in recovery manage high-stress jobs. The counselor supports the client's continued recovery and quality of life."},
{id:"ncm-173",q:"A 35-year-old client has been diagnosed with adult ADHD. They are relieved but also grieving. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to be grateful","Address the relief and grief, provide psychoeducation, support the client's adjustment, and discuss treatment options","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Tell them ADHD isn't a real problem"],answer:1,explanation:"New ADHD diagnosis in adulthood: complex emotional response. Relief (finally understanding), grief (lost time, missed opportunities), identity questions, anxiety, depression. Address both. Provide psychoeducation, support adjustment, and discuss treatment options (medication, behavioral strategies, accommodations, coaching). Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't tell them it's not a real problem. The diagnosis is real. Many adults with ADHD have a long history of struggle before diagnosis. Address the impact and the path forward."},
{id:"ncm-174",q:"A 25-year-old client has been engaging in self-harm as a way to communicate distress. The counselor should:",options:["Ignore it","Assess the function, develop alternative communication skills, use DBT, and address underlying issues","Hospitalize for every episode","Tell them to use words"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm as communication: assess the function (regulation, communication, dissociation, control). Develop alternative communication skills (in DBT — interpersonal effectiveness module), use DBT skills, address underlying issues (trauma, BPD, depression, anxiety). Don't ignore. Don't hospitalize for every episode (unless imminent risk). Don't just tell them to 'use words' (the function is more than words; they need skills and support). The work is long-term, but the client can find better ways to communicate."},
{id:"ncm-175",q:"A 30-year-old client has been having severe marital problems. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to get a divorce","Conduct a comprehensive assessment of the relationship, including the cycle, the strengths, the presenting problems, and the safety","Refer to individual therapy only","Tell them to stay together"],answer:1,explanation:"Marital problems: comprehensive assessment. The cycle, the strengths, the presenting problems, the history, the safety (abuse?), the goals. Use BCT, EFT, Gottman, Imago, etc. Don't tell them to get divorced. Don't tell them to stay together. Don't refer only to individual therapy. Conjoint work is often most helpful. Many couples improve with therapy. The counselor supports informed choice. If abuse is present, individual work is needed first; couples therapy may not be safe."},
{id:"ncm-176",q:"A 22-year-old client is in recovery from opioid use disorder. They are 6 months pregnant. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop MAT","Support continued MAT (methadone or buprenorphine is the standard of care in pregnancy), coordinate with OB, and provide psychosocial support","Refer to detox","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Pregnancy and OUD: MAT (methadone or buprenorphine) is the standard of care. Don't stop MAT (risks withdrawal, relapse, fetal harm, NAS, HIV/HCV). Don't refer to detox (high relapse and fetal risk). Don't hospitalize. Coordinate with OB/GYN, neonatology (NAS is treatable), and case management. Provide psychosocial support. The counselor supports the client's recovery, addresses the parenting role, and prepares for the postpartum period (high-risk for relapse and mental health). Avoid stigma."},
{id:"ncm-177",q:"A 50-year-old client with severe depression has been resistant to multiple treatments. The counselor should:",options:["Discharge as untreatable","Continue to provide therapy, re-evaluate the diagnosis and treatment, consider TMS/esketamine/MAOIs/lithium augmentation, and coordinate with the team","Tell them to be more positive","Recommend ECT immediately"],answer:1,explanation:"Treatment-resistant depression: continue. Re-evaluate: diagnosis, comorbidities, treatment adherence, therapeutic alliance, and treatment fidelity. Consider alternative treatments (TMS, esketamine, MAOIs, lithium augmentation, atypical antipsychotic augmentation, ECT). Coordinate with the psychiatrist. Don't discharge. Don't dismiss. Don't immediately recommend ECT (usually after multiple trials). Stay involved. The counselor is an important anchor. Many 'treatment-resistant' cases respond with persistence and a fresh approach."},
{id:"ncm-178",q:"A 30-year-old client has been using cocaine for 2 years. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use MI, assess the pattern, address the function (often stimulation, social, escape), and develop a treatment plan based on motivation","Hospitalize","Refer to AA only"],answer:1,explanation:"Cocaine use: MI, assess pattern (frequency, amount, route, consequences), function (stimulation, social, escape, coping), comorbidities, motivation. Develop a plan: brief intervention, MI/CBT, contingency management (evidence-based for cocaine), possibly disulfiram or other medication, mutual support (Cocaine Anonymous, NA). Don't demand abstinence. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to AA. Treat comorbidities (depression, ADHD, anxiety). Address lifestyle, relationships, work. Cocaine use is a chronic, relapsing condition."},
{id:"ncm-179",q:"A 25-year-old client has been experiencing severe anxiety and panic. The counselor should:",options:["Begin intensive CBT","Conduct a comprehensive assessment (medical rule-out, comorbidities, severity, history) and develop a treatment plan with the client","Recommend benzodiazepines","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Severe anxiety and panic: comprehensive assessment. Medical rule-out (cardiac, respiratory, endocrine, substance). Comorbidities (depression, OCD, PTSD, substance). Severity, history, prior treatment, family history. Develop a plan with the client: CBT (psychoeducation, cognitive restructuring, exposure to interoceptive and external triggers), SSRIs/SNRIs, relaxation, breathing retraining. Don't begin intensive CBT without assessment. Don't recommend benzos (first-line, dependence, fall risk). Don't hospitalize (rarely appropriate for anxiety alone). Treat the whole person."},
{id:"ncm-180",q:"A 12-year-old has been diagnosed with depression. The parents are asking what to do. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend medication only","Provide education, engage the family, support psychotherapy for the child (CBT, IPT, family therapy), and consider medication evaluation","Tell the parents to wait","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Child depression: education, family engagement, psychotherapy (CBT, IPT-A, family therapy, play therapy as appropriate), consider medication evaluation (SSRIs are first-line in children 8+; fluoxetine is the only FDA-approved antidepressant for children; refer to child psychiatry for medication management). Don't recommend medication only. Don't tell the parents to wait. Don't hospitalize (rarely needed; for severe depression or suicide risk). Address: school, family, peers, sleep, exercise, screen time. Many effective treatments. Engage the child and family."},
{id:"ncm-181",q:"A 40-year-old client has been struggling with low self-esteem and self-criticism for years. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to be more positive","Use CBT (cognitive restructuring), compassion-focused therapy, and self-compassion interventions","Switch to psychoanalysis","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic low self-esteem and self-criticism: CBT (cognitive restructuring of self-critical thoughts), compassion-focused therapy (Gilbert), self-compassion (Neff), ACT (defusion from self-critical thoughts), schema therapy. Don't dismiss. Don't switch to psychoanalysis (less effective for low self-esteem). Don't hospitalize. The therapeutic relationship itself (with UPR, empathy, and congruence) supports self-worth. Many people benefit from targeted interventions. The work is long-term but rewarding."},
{id:"ncm-182",q:"A 35-year-old client has been hearing voices for years. The voices are distressing. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the client the voices are not real","Use CBT for psychosis (CBTp) to help the client manage distress, develop coping strategies, and explore the meaning of the voices","Ignore the voices","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Distressing auditory hallucinations: CBTp. Help the client: develop coping strategies, normalize the experience, explore the meaning of the voices, reduce distress, address the underlying issues, and work on relapse prevention. CBTp is evidence-based. Don't dismiss. Don't ignore. Don't hospitalize (unless safety is at risk). The therapeutic relationship is the basis for change. Voice dialoguing (treating voices as separate but not real) can help. The recovery model applies. Many people find relief."},
{id:"ncm-183",q:"A 60-year-old client has been recently diagnosed with early-stage Alzheimer's. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend long-term care immediately","Address the emotional response, provide support, engage the family, and develop a plan for the future","Tell the client to be positive","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"New diagnosis of Alzheimer's: address the emotional response (shock, grief, fear, anger), provide support, engage the family, develop a plan (medical, legal, financial, support, future care, advance directives), provide psychoeducation, and access resources (Alzheimer's Association). Don't recommend long-term care immediately. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Many people benefit from early intervention, planning, support, and engagement. Address the impact on identity, relationships, and meaning. The counselor is a key support in the early stages."},
{id:"ncm-184",q:"A 14-year-old has been in treatment for self-harm. The teen has not engaged in self-harm for 6 months. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Continue to monitor, develop a relapse prevention plan, address ongoing issues, and discuss termination collaboratively","Discharge immediately","Tell the parents the teen is cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery from self-harm: continue to monitor, develop a relapse prevention plan (warning signs, coping skills, supports, professional numbers), address ongoing issues (DBT, family, trauma, mood), and discuss termination collaboratively. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't discharge. Don't tell the parents the teen is cured. Self-harm often recurs. The work continues. Address the underlying issues. Step down frequency. Many teens in recovery from self-harm need ongoing support. End well."},
{id:"ncm-185",q:"A 50-year-old client has been struggling with adult ADHD and anxiety. The counselor should:",options:["Treat only the anxiety","Address both conditions, coordinate with the prescriber, use CBT for both, and provide behavioral strategies for ADHD","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Comorbid ADHD and anxiety: very common. Address both. CBT for anxiety. Behavioral strategies for ADHD (organization, time management, reminders, breaks, accommodations). Coordinate with the prescriber (medication may help both). Don't treat only one. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize. The whole person. Many people with both conditions do well with combined treatment. The counselor's role: education, skills, support, and coordination."},
{id:"ncm-186",q:"A 25-year-old client has been diagnosed with schizoaffective disorder. The counselor should:",options:["Tell the client they have schizophrenia","Provide education about schizoaffective disorder, support medication adherence, address the mood symptoms, and use CBTp","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Schizoaffective: psychotic symptoms + a major mood episode. Education, support medication adherence, address both psychotic and mood symptoms. CBTp + CBT for the mood component. Coordination with the prescriber. Family education. Don't tell the client they have schizophrenia (inaccurate). Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize (unless acute). The counselor provides psychotherapy and support. Many people with schizoaffective do well with integrated treatment."},
{id:"ncm-187",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in treatment for PTSD for 1 year with good progress. They report a new stressor and worsening symptoms. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to use what they learned","Validate the regression, address the new stressor, reinforce skills, and use this as a learning opportunity","Switch to a different therapy","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"PTSD recovery: setbacks are normal. Validate, don't shame. Address the new stressor, reinforce the skills the client has, use this as a learning opportunity, and adjust the treatment plan if needed. Don't dismiss. Don't switch to a different therapy (PE/EMDR/CPT is still the best). Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Many people experience setbacks in recovery. The relationship and the skills are the basis. Treat the temporary setback as part of the long-term process."},
{id:"ncm-188",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in a serious car accident and is now unable to work. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to find a new job","Address the grief, loss, identity, and adjustment; use CBT and supportive counseling; engage the family; and coordinate with the medical and disability team","Hospitalize","Refer to a vocational counselor only"],answer:1,explanation:"Major accident with disability: address the grief, loss of function, identity, role, and adjustment. Use CBT, supportive counseling, and existential work as needed. Engage the family. Coordinate with the medical team, OT/PT, and disability services. Don't tell them to find a new job. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer only to a vocational counselor. The whole person. Many people adjust with proper support. The counselor helps the client find meaning, identity, and engagement despite the changes."},
{id:"ncm-189",q:"A 22-year-old client has been using methamphetamine. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use MI, assess the pattern, address the function (often stimulation, weight loss, energy, focus, or escape), and develop a treatment plan","Hospitalize","Recommend a quick detox"],answer:1,explanation:"Methamphetamine use: MI, assess pattern, function, comorbidities, and consequences. The function is often stimulation, energy, focus, weight loss, or escape. Develop a plan: MI/CBT, contingency management (the best evidence-based approach for stimulants), possibly MAT (no FDA-approved med for meth, but research on mirtazapine, bupropion, naltrexone, modafinil). Address: medical complications (cardiac, dental, psychiatric), sleep, nutrition, psychosis risk. Don't demand immediate abstinence. Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend quick detox. Long-term support."},
{id:"ncm-190",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of trauma (nightmares, withdrawal, irritability) after witnessing domestic violence. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing immediately","Use TF-CBT (Trauma-Focused CBT) or similar — start with psychoeducation, stabilization, and skills, then processing with the family","Tell the child to forget it","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Child trauma: TF-CBT is first-line. The PRACTICE model: Psychoeducation, Relaxation, Affect modulation, Cognitive processing, Trauma narrative, In vivo mastery, Conjoint sessions, Enhancing future safety. Don't begin trauma processing without stabilization. Don't dismiss. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Address the family. Children process through play, art, and storytelling. The counselor is a key support. The parent who is also affected needs support. Safety is the first priority."},
{id:"ncm-191",q:"A 40-year-old client with severe OCD has been engaging in contamination rituals that take 8 hours per day. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend residential","Build a strong therapeutic relationship, provide psychoeducation, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP","Hospitalize","Tell the client to just stop"],answer:1,explanation:"Severe OCD: build the relationship, provide psychoeducation, develop a fear hierarchy (the most feared item at the top), and begin ERP (gradual exposure with response prevention). SSRIs (often at higher doses) are first-line. Don't recommend residential (often not necessary if the client is willing to do ERP). Don't hospitalize. Don't tell them to 'just stop' (the compulsion is automatic; ERP requires time, support, and motivation). Severe OCD can be treated effectively with intensive ERP + medication. The counselor's patience and support are critical."},
{id:"ncm-192",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in treatment for severe anxiety for 3 months. They report dramatic improvement. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate immediately","Acknowledge progress, develop a relapse prevention plan, and discuss maintenance and termination","Increase the dose of therapy","Tell the client they're cured"],answer:1,explanation:"Substantial progress in anxiety: acknowledge it. Develop a relapse prevention plan. Discuss maintenance (continue for a while to consolidate) and termination (timing, structure, follow-up). Don't terminate abruptly. Don't increase frequency. Don't tell the client they're cured (anxiety disorders are often chronic and recurrent). The work is to consolidate the gains, prepare for setbacks, and end well. Many clients benefit from booster sessions. The counselor supports the client's growth and continued well-being."},
{id:"ncm-193",q:"A 35-year-old client has been dealing with chronic depression for 10 years. The counselor should:",options:["Recommend a quick fix","Provide long-term support, evidence-based therapy (CBT, BA, MBCT, IPT), coordinate with the prescriber, and address chronic issues","Hospitalize","Discharge as chronic"],answer:1,explanation:"Chronic depression: long-term approach. Provide evidence-based therapy (CBT, behavioral activation, MBCT, IPT, CBT for chronic depression). Coordinate with the prescriber. Address: chronic issues, comorbidity, life stress, sleep, exercise, social connection. Don't promise a quick fix. Don't hospitalize (not appropriate for chronic stable depression). Don't discharge as 'chronic' (that abandons the client). Many people with chronic depression can improve with sustained work. The relationship is therapeutic. Stay involved. Don't give up."},
{id:"ncm-194",q:"A 19-year-old client has been engaging in risky sexual behavior. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to be abstinent","Use MI to explore the behavior, address risk reduction (condom use, STI testing, contraception), and discuss values and goals","Refer to a doctor only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Risky sexual behavior: MI, explore the behavior, address risk reduction (condom use, STI testing, contraception, PrEP for HIV if appropriate), discuss values and goals, address substance use (often related). Don't demand abstinence. Don't refer only to a doctor (the counseling relationship is key). Don't hospitalize. Many young people engage in risky behavior. Address: consent, pleasure, relationships, decision-making, self-efficacy, and self-worth. Harm reduction is ethical and effective. Engage the client with respect."},
{id:"ncm-195",q:"A 40-year-old client has been sober for 2 years. They are starting a new relationship. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to avoid relationships","Explore the client's concerns, develop a plan, address triggers, and support the new relationship","Recommend couples therapy immediately","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery and new relationship: explore the client's concerns (early recovery is a vulnerable time). Develop a plan: identify triggers, use coping skills, maintain recovery support, communicate with the partner, attend mutual support, monitor for warning signs. Don't tell them to avoid relationships. Don't recommend couples therapy immediately (let the relationship develop first; couples therapy may be appropriate later). Don't hospitalize. Many people in recovery develop healthy relationships. The counselor supports the client's growth and ongoing recovery."},
{id:"ncm-196",q:"A 28-year-old client has been struggling with anxiety, low self-esteem, and relationship difficulties. The counselor should:",options:["Focus only on anxiety","Conduct a comprehensive assessment and develop an integrated treatment plan that addresses all three areas","Refer to a different counselor","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Multiple presenting issues: comprehensive assessment. Integrated treatment plan that addresses anxiety, self-esteem, and relationships. Often one issue is connected to others (e.g., anxiety → avoidance → low self-esteem → relationship problems). CBT often addresses all three (cognitive restructuring, behavioral experiments, social skills). Don't focus only on one. Don't refer away. Don't hospitalize. The whole person. Many clients do well with integrated work. The relationship is the basis."},
{id:"ncm-197",q:"A 45-year-old client has been through a difficult divorce and is struggling with loneliness. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to find a new relationship","Address the grief, support the client's adjustment, build social connections, and explore values and goals","Refer to a dating app","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Post-divorce loneliness: address the grief, support adjustment, build social connections (friends, family, community, groups, activities), explore values and goals. Don't push dating. Don't refer to a dating app. Don't hospitalize. The first year (or two) after divorce is often a time of grief, identity, and rebuilding. The counselor supports the client's growth, not the rush to a new relationship. Many people find meaning and community in this period."},
{id:"ncm-198",q:"A 14-year-old has been refusing to eat and has been losing weight for 3 months. The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Begin family therapy","Conduct a comprehensive assessment (medical, eating behaviors, family, comorbidities) and refer for medical evaluation given the medical risk","Refer to a nutritionist","Tell the family to force meals"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent eating disorder: comprehensive assessment (medical, eating behaviors, family, comorbidities) and immediate medical evaluation. Medical risk is real (electrolytes, vital signs, BMI, refeeding risk). Don't just begin family therapy without assessment. Don't refer only to a nutritionist. Don't tell the family to force meals. FBT (Maudsley) is first-line for adolescents, but only after medical stabilization. The counselor is key in engaging the family and supporting recovery."},
{id:"ncm-199",q:"A 30-year-old client has been engaging in self-harm during sessions when distressed. The counselor should:",options:["End the session immediately","Stay with the client (don't leave them alone), use grounding and distress tolerance skills, address the function, and develop a safety plan","Hospitalize for every episode","Tell them to stop"],answer:1,explanation:"Self-harm in session: stay with the client (don't leave them alone). Use grounding, distress tolerance, DBT skills. Address the function. Develop a safety plan. Document. Hospitalize only if imminent risk. Don't end the session abruptly. Don't tell them to stop. Don't shame. The counselor's presence is calming. Many clients use in-session self-harm as a last resort; alternative skills are needed. The relationship and the safety plan are critical. Work with the prescriber if needed."},
{id:"ncm-200",q:"A 19-year-old has been struggling with identity (sexual, gender, career, values). The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to pick one","Support the client's exploration, provide a safe space, address family/cultural factors, and use developmentally appropriate interventions","Recommend a specific identity","Refer to a psychiatrist"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent/young adult identity exploration: support the client's exploration. Provide a safe space, address family/cultural factors (which may add stress), use developmentally appropriate interventions (exploration, narrative, person-centered). Many people in late adolescence/early adulthood explore identity (Erikson: identity vs. role confusion). Don't push for a specific identity. Don't tell them to 'pick one' (premature). Don't refer to a psychiatrist (normal developmental process, unless comorbid). The counselor supports the client's growth and discovery."},
{id:"ncm-201",q:"A 35-year-old client has been sober for 5 years. They are now dealing with chronic pain. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to manage without medication","Address the pain without substance use, collaborate with the medical team, use CBT for chronic pain, and address the risk of relapse","Hospitalize","Recommend opioids"],answer:1,explanation:"Pain in recovery: address without substance use. Collaborate with the medical team. CBT for chronic pain (pacing, activity, sleep, mood, coping). Discuss pain management options (non-opioid preferred, but some patients in recovery can take prescribed opioids with proper support). Don't tell them to manage without medication (pain is real). Don't hospitalize. Don't recommend opioids unilaterally. Address the risk of relapse (high stress). The counselor supports the client's recovery and effective pain management."},
{id:"ncm-202",q:"A 30-year-old client has been experiencing flashbacks and dissociation. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing immediately","Use a phased approach: stabilization (grounding, safety, coping), then processing (PE, EMDR, CPT), then integration","Tell the client the memories are not real","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Flashbacks and dissociation: phased trauma approach. Stabilization first: grounding, safety, coping, regulation. Processing when stable. Integration. Don't begin processing without stabilization (risk of re-traumatization). Don't tell the client the memories are not real (the experience is real). Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). Address: the present, the triggers, the body, the relationships, the meaning. The therapeutic relationship is the basis. Many people benefit from a careful, phased approach."},
{id:"ncm-203",q:"A 12-year-old has been exhibiting symptoms of OCD (intrusive thoughts about contamination, washing hands for hours). The counselor should:",options:["Tell the child to stop","Conduct a multi-informant assessment, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP with the family","Refer to a psychiatrist only","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Child OCD: multi-informant assessment, family engagement, develop a fear hierarchy, and begin ERP (with the parents as co-therapists). SSRIs are first-line medication (collaborate with child psychiatry). The parents' accommodation is a key target. Don't tell the child to stop. Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. Don't hospitalize. Family-based CBT for OCD is evidence-based. The counselor's patience and the family's support are critical. Many children with OCD improve with proper treatment."},
{id:"ncm-204",q:"A 45-year-old client with chronic depression is in ongoing treatment. They report using alcohol more on weekends. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to stop","Use MI, assess the use, address the function, and develop a plan based on motivation","Refer to AA immediately","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Substance use in chronic depression: MI, assess use, function (coping, sleep, social), motivation, consequences. Develop a plan based on the client's goals (some clients may want moderation, others abstinence; both can be valid). Don't demand abstinence. Don't refer to AA immediately (may not fit). Don't hospitalize (not appropriate for moderate use). Address: depression, sleep, coping, social support. Treat the whole person. Many people with depression benefit from harm reduction."},
{id:"ncm-205",q:"A 25-year-old client with ADHD has been struggling with rejection sensitivity. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they're too sensitive","Validate the experience, use CBT, address the negative self-talk, and provide skills for emotion regulation","Switch to a different therapy","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Rejection Sensitive Dysphoria (RSD) — common in ADHD: validate the experience, use CBT (cognitive restructuring, behavioral experiments), address the negative self-talk, and provide emotion regulation skills. Some clients benefit from medication (often stimulants help; alpha-2 agonists). Don't dismiss. Don't switch. Don't hospitalize. The therapeutic relationship is critical. Address: the past, the present, the relationships, the self-worth, and the skills. Many people with RSD find relief with proper support."},
{id:"ncm-206",q:"A 30-year-old client has been in therapy for depression for 6 weeks. They report partial improvement but still feel hopeless. The counselor should:",options:["Terminate treatment","Continue treatment, reassess (comorbidities, stressors, support, medication), use behavioral activation, and develop a relapse prevention plan","Tell the client to be more positive","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Partial improvement: continue. Reassess: comorbidities, stressors, support, sleep, medication adherence, therapeutic alliance. Use behavioral activation. Develop a relapse prevention plan. Don't terminate prematurely. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Many clients improve gradually. The relationship and the structure are important. Some clients need medication augmentation or change. Some need more sessions. Stay involved. Don't give up."},
{id:"ncm-207",q:"A 14-year-old has been experiencing a major depressive episode after a friend's suicide. The counselor should:",options:["Begin trauma processing","Address the depression and grief, monitor for suicide risk, engage the family, and provide trauma-focused support","Hospitalize for safety","Refer to a psychiatrist only"],answer:1,explanation:"Adolescent depression after friend's suicide: assess for suicide risk first. Address the depression and grief. Engage the family. Provide trauma-focused support (TF-CBT, grief work). Don't begin trauma processing without stabilization. Don't hospitalize (unless imminent risk). Don't refer only to a psychiatrist. The combination of depression, grief, and suicide exposure is a serious clinical picture. Postvention is important (school, community). Many adolescents benefit from early intervention."},
{id:"ncm-208",q:"A 35-year-old client has been in long-term recovery from alcohol use disorder. They are now struggling with chronic depression. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them to focus on recovery","Address the depression with evidence-based treatment (CBT, BA, medication referral), coordinate with the recovery support system, and treat the whole person","Recommend more AA meetings","Hospitalize"],answer:1,explanation:"Depression in long-term recovery: treat it. Don't dismiss. Don't tell them to focus only on recovery. Don't recommend more AA (it doesn't treat depression). Don't hospitalize (unless severe). Many people in long-term recovery develop new mental health issues (often related to underlying mood, trauma, life changes). Use CBT, behavioral activation, and medication referral (SSRIs are first-line; bupropion may be preferred for some but beware of seizure risk). Coordinate with the recovery support system. The whole person."},
{id:"ncm-209",q:"A 12-year-old has been engaging in bullying online (cyberbullying). The counselor should FIRST:",options:["Take away the device","Conduct a comprehensive assessment, address the behavior, engage the family, collaborate with the school, and teach digital citizenship","Hospitalize","Tell the parents to monitor more"],answer:1,explanation:"Cyberbullying: comprehensive assessment. Why is the child bullying? (Modeling, peer dynamics, social skills deficits, trauma, conduct disorder, ADHD). Address the behavior, engage the family, collaborate with the school, and teach digital citizenship. Don't take away the device (without addressing the underlying issue). Don't hospitalize. Don't rely on more parental monitoring (often ineffective). The victim also needs support. Many cases resolve with intervention. The counselor is key."},
{id:"ncm-210",q:"A 50-year-old client has been dealing with severe chronic mental illness for 20 years. They want to live independently. The counselor should:",options:["Tell them they can't","Assess their current functioning, develop a supported housing plan, coordinate with ACT or case management, and support the client's goal","Hospitalize","Refer to a nursing home"],answer:1,explanation:"Recovery goal: independent living. Assess functioning, develop a supported housing plan (Housing First is evidence-based), coordinate with ACT (Assertive Community Treatment) or case management, and support the client's goal. Don't dismiss. Don't hospitalize. Don't refer to a nursing home. Many people with severe mental illness can live independently with proper support. The counselor supports the client's autonomy and choice. The recovery model emphasizes hope, empowerment, and community."}
);
